<TITLE> Stocks end higher on blue chips </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 02 (bdnews24.com)Indices on the country's twin bourses ended higher Wednesday, driven by blue chips. "Investors were keen to trade in market majors," said an official with brokerage house IDLC Securities. "But trading was low." Although the indices ended on a positive note, turnover slipped. "Despite the rise in indices, selling led to a significant decrease in turnover," said Bashir Ahmed, an investment consultant. Investors, especially small ones, were reluctant to trade following regulatory interventions, Bashir, who is with brokerage house Stocks & Bonds, told bdnews24.com. The DGEN or general index rose 28.73 points or 0.95 percent at 3029.23. The DSI or all-share price index advanced 14.80 points or 0.57 percent to finish at 2602.82, while the DSE-20 blue-chip index gained 34.21 points or 1.34 percent to 2579.38. Turnover fell to Tk 2.58 billion from Monday's Tk 3.30 billion, with 20,022,180 shares changing hands. Of the traded issues, 115 declined, 90 gained and 11 remained unchanged. Square Pharmaceuticals topped the turnover board, rising 1.53 percent to Tk 5542.75. AIMS 1st Mutual Fund slumped 15.60 percent to Tk 12.93. Lanka Bangla Finance finished at Tk 215, slipping 2.84 percent from Monday's closing. Uttara Bank gained 6.60 percent to Tk 3003. Apex Adelchi Footwear ended on Tk 3886.50, gaining 6.34 percent. Other scrips on the turnover boardPadma Oil, NBL and Prime Finance and Investmentadvanced. Fareast Life Insurance and Grameen One Mutual Fund lost. All indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange closed upbeat also. The CSCX or selective categories index closed 73.59 points or 1.25 percent higher at 5927.17, while the CASPI or all-share price index finished at 9146.93, up 96.37 points or 1.06 percent. The CSE-30 surged 169.54 points or 2.10 percent to end on 8206.56. Turnover on the port city's bourse plunged to Tk 281.79 million from Tk 344.14 million the previous dayfrom 2,694,526 traded shares. bdn
